# Payments Domain – Business Rules

# Purpose

This document defines the enforceable business rules governing the Payments Domain. These rules represent non-negotiable constraints derived from business requirements, regulatory obligations, and system integrity needs.

All implementations, workflows, and integrations must comply with these rules.

---

# Business Rules

---

## RULE-001: Every payment must have a unique identifier

Source: Business/Architecture/Compliance

Each payment must be assigned a globally unique identifier at creation time to ensure traceability and prevent duplication across systems.

---

## RULE-002: Payment amounts must be greater than zero

Source: Business/Finance/Validation

Payments must have a strictly positive amount. Zero or negative values are not permitted under any circumstance.

---

## RULE-003: Payments must follow a valid lifecycle state transition

Source: Architecture/Domain Model/Business

A payment must only transition through predefined valid states. Skipping states or transitioning to invalid states is not allowed.

---

## RULE-004: Payments are immutable in terminal states

Source: Compliance/Architecture/Finance

Once a payment reaches a terminal state (Completed, Failed, Cancelled), it must not be modified.

---

## RULE-005: Idempotency must be enforced for all payment creation requests

Source: Architecture/Engineering/Platform

Repeated requests with the same idempotency key must result in the same payment outcome without duplication.

---

## RULE-006: Each payment must be processed through exactly one provider per transaction attempt

Source: Integration/Architecture/Engineering

A single transaction attempt must be executed against one payment provider only.

---

## RULE-007: A payment may have multiple transaction attempts but only one successful outcome

Source: Architecture/Domain Model/Business

Multiple retries are allowed, but only one successful transaction is required to complete a payment.

---

## RULE-008: Refunds cannot exceed the original payment amount

Source: Finance/Compliance

The total sum of refunds associated with a payment must not exceed the original payment amount.

---

## RULE-009: Refunds can only be created for completed payments

Source: Finance/Business Rules/Domain Model

Refund operations are only valid if the original payment is in a Completed state.

---

## RULE-010: Payment state changes must be auditable

Source: Compliance/Audit/Architecture

Every change in payment state must be recorded in an immutable audit trail for traceability and compliance.

---

## RULE-011: External payment providers are not trusted sources of truth

Source: Architecture/Integration/Domain Model

Provider responses must be validated and normalized before updating internal payment state.

---

## RULE-012: Payment processing must be resilient to retries and partial failures

Source: Engineering/Resilience/Architecture

Payment operations must be designed to handle retries without causing inconsistent state or duplication.

---

## RULE-013: Payments must be traceable end-to-end across all systems

Source: Compliance/Observability/Architecture

Every payment must be traceable from initiation through all processing stages and final outcome.

---

## RULE-014: Currency must conform to ISO 4217 standard

Source: Finance/Integration/Validation

All payment currency values must use valid ISO 4217 currency codes.

---

## RULE-015: Failed payments must include a failure reason

Source: Operations/Support/Engineering

Any payment that transitions to a Failed state must include a structured reason for failure.

---

## RULE-016: Payment processing must not block upstream systems

Source: Architecture/Performance/Platform

Payment execution must be designed to avoid blocking or degrading upstream systems such as Orders or Billing.

---

## RULE-017: All payment events must be immutable once published

Source: Architecture/Eventing/Platform

Published domain events must not be modified or deleted after emission.

---

# Notes

* These rules are authoritative within the Payments Domain.
* Any deviation requires a documented Architecture Decision Record (ADR).
* New rules must be reviewed by both Engineering and Business stakeholders before adoption.
